 0, ...]` → `u64_le = 2` → slot = `2 % 2 = 0` → Player A\n\nBoth give Player A! That works. Let me use the same data format as coinflip's existing mock.\n\nActually let me verify — the on-chain mock `read_orao_randomness` for the lordofrngs program: it reads the first 32 bytes. `randomness[0..8]` = `[2, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0]` → `u64_le = 2`. With 2 total entries → `2 % 2 = 0` → slot 0 → Player A (creator, first entry).\n\nThe frontend `readVrfRandomness` reads bytes `[8..40]` → `[2, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, ...]` → `u64_le = 2` → `2 % 2 = 0` → slot 0 → Player A.\n\nBoth agree. Player A wins. \n\nNow let me start implementing. I'll work on all the files needed."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2686,"cache_read_input_tokens":105410,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":2686},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"3430a832-47ac-41dd-bbc6-e4b8a98508e0","uuid":"872e2f99-729b-4e56-a09e-69f8f2ff06a8"}
